post_cb({"37421194": {"CommentCount": "9", "ViewCount": "102", "CreationDate": "2016-05-24T18:26:28.130", "LastActivityDate": "2016-05-24T18:26:28.130", "Title": "array in std::tuple passed to std::tuple_cat in decltype error - g++ vs clang++ - which compiler is right", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "37421194", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>Consider the code below:</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;tuple&gt;\n\nint main() {\n   std::tuple&lt;char[2], int&gt; t1;\n   std::tuple&lt;int&gt; t2;\n   decltype(std::tuple_cat(t1, t2)) t3;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>It compiles fine with <code>g++</code> (in version &gt;= 5.2) and <code>icc</code> (13.0.1), but not in <code>clang++</code> and older versions of <code>g++</code> where it gives nasty error:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_37421194_37421194_0\">array initializer must be an initializer list or string literal</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>My hunch tells me that the code shouldn't compile and <code>clang++</code> and older versions of <code>g++</code> are actually right here, but want to take a second opinion.</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><g++><language-lawyer><clang++>", "OwnerUserId": "4324224", "AnswerCount": "0"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_37421194_37421194_0": {"section_id": 3308, "quality": 0.5714285714285714, "length": 4}}, "n3337": {"so_37421194_37421194_0": {"section_id": 3178, "quality": 0.5714285714285714, "length": 4}}, "n4659": {"so_37421194_37421194_0": {"section_id": 657, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "length": 5}}}});